{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628014"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17161"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17161"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.38,0.03,0.51,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77001"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9851"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1003"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5020"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9833"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23082"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23086"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77001"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K is a fat-soluble vitamin that plays a crucial role in blood coagulation. It is obtained through dietary sources and synthesis by intestinal bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of vitamin K in blood coagulation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitates thrombin activation of platelets","Promotes synthesis of coagulation proteins","Enhances calcium binding to phospholipids","Functions as carboxylation reaction cofactor","Stabilises fibrin polymer formation"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin K \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctions as carboxylation reaction cofactor\u003C/strong\u003E through gamma-glutamyl carboxylase enzyme. This enzyme adds carboxyl groups to specific glutamic acid residues on clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X. The carboxylation enables these factors to bind calcium ions, which is essential for their activation in the coagulation cascade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates thrombin activation of platelets\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin K does not have a direct role in platelet activation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPromotes synthesis of coagulation proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin K is not directly involved in protein synthesis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhances calcium binding to phospholipids\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin K does not affect calcium-phospholipid interactions\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises fibrin polymer formation\u003C/strong\u003E - Vitamin K is not involved in fibrin polymerisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWithout vitamin K, these clotting factors cannot be carboxylated and remain inactive, leading to an increased bleeding risk. This is the basis for how warfarin (a vitamin K antagonist) works as an anticoagulant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Vitamin K is essential for the carboxylation of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X in the liver.","Vitamin K acts as a cofactor for gamma-glutamyl carboxylase which adds carboxyl groups to glutamic acid residues.","Carboxylation of clotting factors enables them to bind calcium ions, which is necessary for their activation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury, C., Rieke, F., Hille, B., Bothwell, M., \u0026 Tuthill, J. (2023) Physiology. Simple Book Publishing. https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17161"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:10:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:11:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9851"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77001"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"